		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2012 SI"></a><br><code>sle2012s/paper01</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2012 SI</a> paper:</span><br><i>A tutorial on metamodelling for grammar researchers</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/RichardFPaige.html">Richard F. Paige</a>, <a href="../profile/DimitriosSKolovos.html">Dimitrios S. Kolovos</a>, <a href="../profile/FionaPolack.html">Fiona Polack</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.scico.2014.05.007">10.1016/j.scico.2014.05.007</a></li>
<li>Extended version of <a href="../sle2012/paper04.html"><em>Metamodelling for Grammarware Researchers</em></a> (SLE 2012)</li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagM">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> The central goal is to explain metamodels as a language-definition formalism (abstract syntax) and relate them to grammar-based definitions.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> The tutorial emphasises metamodelling infrastructures and tooling (e.g., modelware ecosystems) as the practical basis for language engineering tasks.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t6d.html"><span class="tagL">T6D: Synergies</span></a><ul><li> A core theme is bridging “grammarware” and “modelware”, highlighting how the two approaches can be used together rather than competitively.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1a.html"><span class="tagL">T1A: Design</span></a><ul><li> It discusses language-definition choices (metamodels vs grammars) and their implications for designing and implementing languages.
</li></ul></li></ul>
		<clear/>
